## SharePoint Configuration (Optional)

To save execution screenshots to SharePoint in case of RPA error, add sharepoint_config to the Browser creation with the following keys:
* `site_id`
* `app_id`
* `app_secret`
* `tenant_id`

## SeleniumExceptions

`BaseSelenium` (and, by alias, `Browser`) exposes a nested `SeleniumExceptions` class that bundles the Selenium exception hierarchy for convenient `except` clauses.

- `SeleniumExceptions.ALL` is a `tuple[type, ...]` containing every `Exception` subclass defined in `selenium.common.exceptions` (discovered at import time via `inspect.getmembers`). Typical members include `WebDriverException`, `TimeoutException`, `NoSuchElementException`, `StaleElementReferenceException`, `ElementClickInterceptedException`, etc.

Use it to catch any Selenium-originating error in one shot:

```python
from wcp_library.browser_automation.browser import Browser

with Browser(Browser.Firefox, options) as driver:
    try:
        driver.press_button("#submit")
    except Browser.SeleniumExceptions.ALL:
        # handle any Selenium error
        ...
```

### locator

The HTML locator used to find a web element on a page. Used by `UIInteractions` methods.

- **css**: *(Default)* Selects elements using CSS selectors.
- **id**: Selects an element by its unique ID attribute.
- **name**: Selects elements by the value of their `name` attribute.
- **class**: Selects elements by their class name.
- **tag**: Selects elements by their HTML tag name.
- **xpath**: Selects elements using XPath expressions.
- **link_text**: Selects anchor elements whose visible text matches exactly.
- **partial_link_text**: Selects anchor elements whose visible text contains the specified substring.

### Expected Condition (single element — `UIInteractions`)

- **clickable**: *(Default)* Waits until the element is both visible and enabled so that it can be clicked.
- **present**: Waits until the element is present in the DOM, regardless of its visibility.
- **visible**: Waits until the element is visible on the page.
- **selected**: Waits until the element is selected (useful for checkboxes, radio buttons, etc.).
- **frame_available**: Waits until the specified frame is available.

### Expected Condition (multiple elements — `UIInteractions`)

- **visible**: *(Default)* Waits until all the elements are visible on the page.
- **present**: Waits until all the elements are present in the DOM, regardless of their visibility.

### Expected Condition (WebElement — `WEInteractions`)

- **clickable**: *(Default)* Waits until the element is both visible and enabled so that it can be clicked.
- **visible**: Waits until the element is present in the DOM and visible.
- **invisible**: Waits until the element is no longer visible.
- **selected**: Waits until the element is selected (useful for checkboxes, radio buttons, etc.).
- **staleness**: Waits until the element is no longer attached to the DOM.

### Wait Time

By default it will use the implicit timeout set in the browser options (converted from milliseconds to seconds) but can be overridden per call.

# Functions

## Browser Interactions

### go_to

`go_to(self, url: str | URL) -> None`

Navigate to the specified URL.

```python
driver.go_to(url)
```

### refresh_page

`refresh_page(self) -> None`

Refresh the current page.

```python
driver.refresh_page()
```

### get_url

`get_url(self) -> str`

Get the current URL of the page.

```python
driver.get_url()
```

### get_title

`get_title(self) -> str`

Get the title of the current page.

```python
driver.get_title()
```

### switch_to_window

`switch_to_window(self, window_handle: str | list | None = None) -> dict | None`

Switch the browser context to a new window. If none is specified, it will switch to the next opened window and return a dictionary with the original, new, and all window handles.

```python
driver.switch_to_window(window_handle=window_handle)
```

### close_window

`close_window(self, window_handle: str | None = None) -> None`

Close a browser window. If none is specified, the window with current focus will be closed.

```python
driver.close_window(window_handle=window_handle)
```

### take_screenshot

`take_screenshot(self, file_path: Path) -> None`

Take a screenshot of the current page and save it to the specified file path.

```python
driver.take_screenshot(file_path)
```

### force_wait

`force_wait(wait_time: int | float) -> None`

Block execution for a fixed duration (in seconds).

```python
driver.force_wait(5)
```

### execute_script

`execute_script(self, script: str, *args) -> Any`

Execute JavaScript code in the browser context.

```python
driver.execute_script("return document.title;")
driver.execute_script("arguments[0].click();", element)
```

## HTML Locator Interactions (`UIInteractions`)

### get_element

`get_element(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> WebElement`

Get a single WebElement based on the expected condition, locator, and element value.

```python
driver.get_element(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition, wait_time=wait_time)
```

### get_multiple_elements

`get_multiple_elements(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> list[WebElement]`

Get a list of WebElements based on the expected condition, locator, and element value.

```python
driver.get_multiple_elements(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition, wait_time=wait_time)
```

### get_first_element

`get_first_element(self, elements: list[dict], wait_time: float | None = 0) -> WebElement`

Get the first available WebElement from a list of element dictionaries. Each dictionary must contain an `element` key and may optionally contain `locator` (default `"css"`) and `expected_condition` (default `"clickable"`).

```python
driver.get_first_element([
    {"element": "#btn-primary", "locator": "css"},
    {"element": "//button[@id='fallback']", "locator": "xpath"},
], wait_time=wait_time)
```

### get_text

`get_text(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> str`

Get the visible text of an element.

```python
driver.get_text(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition)
```

### get_value

`get_value(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> str`

Get the `value` attribute of an element.

```python
driver.get_value(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition)
```

### get_table

`get_table(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> pd.DataFrame`

Parse an HTML `<table>` element into a pandas DataFrame.

```python
driver.get_table(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition)
```

### press_button

`press_button(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> None`

Click an element.

```python
driver.press_button(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition)
```

### enter_text

`enter_text(self, text: str, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> None`

Clear and populate a text field with the provided text.

```python
driver.enter_text(text, element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition)
```

### set_checkbox_state

`set_checkbox_state(self, state: bool, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> None`

Set a checkbox to the desired state.

```python
driver.set_checkbox_state(True, element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition)
```

### set_select_option

`set_select_option(self, option: str, element_value: str, select_type: str | None = None, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> None`

Choose an option from a `<select>` dropdown. `select_type` can be specified:

- **value**: *(Default)* Selects the option based on the value of its `value` attribute.
- **visible_text**: Selects the option that displays the specified text to the user.
- **index**: Selects the option based on its position (zero-based index) in the dropdown list.

```python
driver.set_select_option(option, element_value, select_type="visible_text", locator=locator)
```

### web_page_contains

`web_page_contains(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> WebElement | bool`

Check whether an element is present on the page. Returns the element if found, otherwise `False`.

```python
driver.web_page_contains(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition, wait_time=wait_time)
```

### wait_for_element

`wait_for_element(self, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, expected_condition: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> WebElement`

Block until an element meets the expected condition.

```python
driver.wait_for_element(element_value, locator=locator, expected_condition=expected_condition, wait_time=wait_time)
```

### text_is_present

`text_is_present(self, text: str, element_value: str, locator: str | None = None, text_location: str | None = None, wait_time: float | None = 0) -> WebElement | bool`

Check whether the specified text is present within an element. Returns the element if found, otherwise `False`. `text_location` can be specified:

- **anywhere**: *(Default)* Checks if the specified text appears anywhere within the element.
- **attribute**: Checks if the specified text is present in a specific attribute of the element.
- **value**: Checks if the specified text matches the value attribute of the element.

```python
driver.text_is_present(text, element_value, locator=locator, text_location=text_location, wait_time=wait_time)
```

